131Ch 9:37 Gedor, Ahio, Zechariah and Mikloth.
131Ch 9:38 Mikloth was the father of Shimeam. They too lived near their relatives in Jerusalem.
131Ch 9:39 Ner was the father of Kish, Kish the father of Saul, and Saul the father of Jonathan, Malki-Shua, Abinadab and Esh-Baal.
131Ch 9:40 The son of Jonathan£º Merib-Baal, who was the father of Micah.
131Ch 9:41 The sons of Micah£º Pithon, Melech, Tahrea and Ahaz.
131Ch 9:42 Ahaz was the father of Jadah, Jadah was the father of Alemeth, Azmaveth and Zimri, and Zimri was the father of Moza.
131Ch 9:43 Moza was the father of Binea; Rephaiah was his son, Eleasah his son and Azel his son.
131Ch 9:44 Azel had six sons, and these were their names£º Azrikam, Bokeru, Ishmael, Sheariah, Obadiah and Hanan. These were the sons of Azel.
131Ch 10:1 Now the Philistines fought against Israel; the Israelites fled before them, and many fell slain on Mount Gilboa.
131Ch 10:2 The Philistines pressed hard after Saul and his sons, and they killed his sons Jonathan, Abinadab and Malki-Shua.
131Ch 10:3 The fighting grew fierce around Saul, and when the archers overtook him, they wounded him.
131Ch 10:4 Saul said to his armor-bearer, "Draw your sword and run me through, or these uncircumcised fellows will come and abuse me." But his armor-bearer was terrified and would not do it; so Saul took his own sword and fell on it.
131Ch 10:5 When the armor-bearer saw that Saul was dead, he too fell on his sword and died.
131Ch 10:6 So Saul and his three sons died, and all his house died together.
131Ch 10:7 When all the Israelites in the valley saw that the army had fled and that Saul and his sons had died, they abandoned their towns and fled. And the Philistines came and occupied them.
131Ch 10:8 The next day, when the Philistines came to strip the dead, they found Saul and his sons fallen on Mount Gilboa.
131Ch 10:9 They stripped him and took his head and his armor, and sent messengers throughout the land of the Philistines to proclaim the news among their idols and their people.
131Ch 10:10 They put his armor in the temple of their gods and hung up his head in the temple of Dagon.
131Ch 10:11 When all the inhabitants of Jabesh Gilead heard of everything the Philistines had done to Saul,
131Ch 10:12 all their valiant men went and took the bodies of Saul and his sons and brought them to Jabesh. Then they buried their bones under the great tree in Jabesh, and they fasted seven days.
131Ch 10:13 Saul died because he was unfaithful to the LORD; he did not keep the word of the LORD and even consulted a medium for guidance,
131Ch 10:14 and did not inquire of the LORD. So the LORD put him to death and turned the kingdom over to David son of Jesse.
131Ch 11:1 All Israel came together to David at Hebron and said, "We are your own flesh and blood.
131Ch 11:2 In the past, even while Saul was king, you were the one who led Israel on their military campaigns. And the LORD your God said to you, 'You will shepherd my people Israel, and you will become their ruler.'"
131Ch 11:3 When all the elders of Israel had come to King David at Hebron, he made a compact with them at Hebron before the LORD, and they anointed David king over Israel, as the LORD had promised through Samuel.
131Ch 11:4 David and all the Israelites marched to Jerusalem (that is, Jebus). The Jebusites who lived there
131Ch 11:5 said to David, "You will not get in here." Nevertheless, David captured the fortress of Zion, the City of David.
131Ch 11:6 David had said, "Whoever leads the attack on the Jebusites will become commander-in-chief." Joab son of Zeruiah went up first, and so he received the command.
131Ch 11:7 David then took up residence in the fortress, and so it was called the City of David.
131Ch 11:8 He built up the city around it, from the supporting terraces to the surrounding wall, while Joab restored the rest of the city.
131Ch 11:9 And David became more and more powerful, because the LORD Almighty was with him.
131Ch 11:10 These were the chiefs of David's mighty men--they, together with all Israel, gave his kingship strong support to extend it over the whole land, as the LORD had promised--
131Ch 11:11 this is the list of David's mighty men£º Jashobeam, a Hacmonite, was chief of the officers; he raised his spear against three hundred men, whom he killed in one encounter.
131Ch 11:12 Next to him was Eleazar son of Dodai the Ahohite, one of the three mighty men.
131Ch 11:13 He was with David at Pas Dammim when the Philistines gathered there for battle. At a place where there was a field full of barley, the troops fled from the Philistines.
131Ch 11:14 But they took their stand in the middle of the field. They defended it and struck the Philistines down, and the LORD brought about a great victory.
131Ch 11:15 Three of the thirty chiefs came down to David to the rock at the cave of Adullam, while a band of Philistines was encamped in the Valley of Rephaim.
131Ch 11:16 At that time David was in the stronghold, and the Philistine garrison was at Bethlehem.
131Ch 11:17 David longed for water and said, "Oh, that someone would get me a drink of water from the well near the gate of Bethlehem!"
131Ch 11:18 So the Three broke through the Philistine lines, drew water from the well near the gate of Bethlehem and carried it back to David. But he refused to drink it; instead, he poured it out before the LORD.
131Ch 11:19 "God forbid that I should do this!" he said. "Should I drink the blood of these men who went at the risk of their lives?" Because they risked their lives to bring it back, David would not drink it. Such were the exploits of the three mighty men.
131Ch 11:20 Abishai the brother of Joab was chief of the Three. He raised his spear against three hundred men, whom he killed, and so he became as famous as the Three.
131Ch 11:21 He was doubly honored above the Three and became their commander, even though he was not included among them.
131Ch 11:22 Benaiah son of Jehoiada was a valiant fighter from Kabzeel, who performed great exploits. He struck down two of Moab's best men. He also went down into a pit on a snowy day and killed a lion.
131Ch 11:23 And he struck down an Egyptian who was seven and a half feet tall. Although the Egyptian had a spear like a weaver's rod in his hand, Benaiah went against him with a club. He snatched the spear from the Egyptian's hand and killed him with his own spear.
131Ch 11:24 Such were the exploits of Benaiah son of Jehoiada; he too was as famous as the three mighty men.
131Ch 11:25 He was held in greater honor than any of the Thirty, but he was not included among the Three. And David put him in charge of his bodyguard.
131Ch 11:26 The mighty men were£º Asahel the brother of Joab, Elhanan son of Dodo from Bethlehem,
131Ch 11:27 Shammoth the Harorite, Helez the Pelonite,
131Ch 11:28 Ira son of Ikkesh from Tekoa, Abiezer from Anathoth,
131Ch 11:29 Sibbecai the Hushathite, Ilai the Ahohite,
131Ch 11:30 Maharai the Netophathite, Heled son of Baanah the Netophathite,
131Ch 11:31 Ithai son of Ribai from Gibeah in Benjamin, Benaiah the Pirathonite,
131Ch 11:32 Hurai from the ravines of Gaash, Abiel the Arbathite,
131Ch 11:33 Azmaveth the Baharumite, Eliahba the Shaalbonite,
131Ch 11:34 the sons of Hashem the Gizonite, Jonathan son of Shagee the Hararite,
131Ch 11:35 Ahiam son of Sacar the Hararite, Eliphal son of Ur,
131Ch 11:36 Hepher the Mekerathite, Ahijah the Pelonite,
131Ch 11:37 Hezro the Carmelite, Naarai son of Ezbai,
131Ch 11:38 Joel the brother of Nathan, Mibhar son of Hagri,
131Ch 11:39 Zelek the Ammonite, Naharai the Berothite, the armor-bearer of Joab son of Zeruiah,
131Ch 11:40 Ira the Ithrite, Gareb the Ithrite,
131Ch 11:41 Uriah the Hittite, Zabad son of Ahlai,
131Ch 11:42 Adina son of Shiza the Reubenite, who was chief of the Reubenites, and the thirty with him,
131Ch 11:43 Hanan son of Maacah, Joshaphat the Mithnite,
131Ch 11:44 Uzzia the Ashterathite, Shama and Jeiel the sons of Hotham the Aroerite,
131Ch 11:45 Jediael son of Shimri, his brother Joha the Tizite,
131Ch 11:46 Eliel the Mahavite, Jeribai and Joshaviah the sons of Elnaam, Ithmah the Moabite,
131Ch 11:47 Eliel, Obed and Jaasiel the Mezobaite.
131Ch 12:1 These were the men who came to David at Ziklag, while he was banished from the presence of Saul son of Kish (they were among the warriors who helped him in battle;
131Ch 12:2 they were armed with bows and were able to shoot arrows or to sling stones right-handed or left-handed; they were kinsmen of Saul from the tribe of Benjamin)£º
131Ch 12:3 Ahiezer their chief and Joash the sons of Shemaah the Gibeathite; Jeziel and Pelet the sons of Azmaveth; Beracah, Jehu the Anathothite,
131Ch 12:4 and Ishmaiah the Gibeonite, a mighty man among the Thirty, who was a leader of the Thirty; Jeremiah, Jahaziel, Johanan, Jozabad the Gederathite,
131Ch 12:5 Eluzai, Jerimoth, Bealiah, Shemariah and Shephatiah the Haruphite;
131Ch 12:6 Elkanah, Isshiah, Azarel, Joezer and Jashobeam the Korahites;
131Ch 12:7 and Joelah and Zebadiah the sons of Jeroham from Gedor.
131Ch 12:8 Some Gadites defected to David at his stronghold in the desert. They were brave warriors, ready for battle and able to handle the shield and spear. Their faces were the faces of lions, and they were as swift as gazelles in the mountains.
131Ch 12:9 Ezer was the chief, Obadiah the second in command, Eliab the third,
131Ch 12:10 Mishmannah the fourth, Jeremiah the fifth,
131Ch 12:11 Attai the sixth, Eliel the seventh,
131Ch 12:12 Johanan the eighth, Elzabad the ninth,
131Ch 12:13 Jeremiah the tenth and Macbannai the eleventh.
131Ch 12:14 These Gadites were army commanders; the least was a match for a hundred, and the greatest for a thousand.
131Ch 12:15 It was they who crossed the Jordan in the first month when it was overflowing all its banks, and they put to flight everyone living in the valleys, to the east and to the west.
131Ch 12:16 Other Benjamites and some men from Judah also came to David in his stronghold.
131Ch 12:17 David went out to meet them and said to them, "If you have come to me in peace, to help me, I am ready to have you unite with me. But if you have come to betray me to my enemies when my hands are free from violence, may the God of our fathers see it and judge you."
131Ch 12:18 Then the Spirit came upon Amasai, chief of the Thirty, and he said£º "We are yours, O David! We are with you, O son of Jesse! Success, success to you, and success to those who help you, for your God will help you." So David received them and made them leaders of his raiding bands.
131Ch 12:19 Some of the men of Manasseh defected to David when he went with the Philistines to fight against Saul. (He and his men did not help the Philistines because, after consultation, their rulers sent him away. They said, "It will cost us our heads if he deserts to his master Saul.")
131Ch 12:20 When David went to Ziklag, these were the men of Manasseh who defected to him£º Adnah, Jozabad, Jediael, Michael, Jozabad, Elihu and Zillethai, leaders of units of a thousand in Manasseh.
131Ch 12:21 They helped David against raiding bands, for all of them were brave warriors, and they were commanders in his army.
131Ch 12:22 Day after day men came to help David, until he had a great army, like the army of God.
131Ch 12:23 These are the numbers of the men armed for battle who came to David at Hebron to turn Saul's kingdom over to him, as the LORD had said£º
131Ch 12:24 men of Judah, carrying shield and spear--6,800 armed for battle;
131Ch 12:25 men of Simeon, warriors ready for battle--7,100;
131Ch 12:26 men of Levi--4,600,
131Ch 12:27 including Jehoiada, leader of the family of Aaron, with 3,700 men,
131Ch 12:28 and Zadok, a brave young warrior, with 22 officers from his family;
131Ch 12:29 men of Benjamin, Saul's kinsmen--3,000, most of whom had remained loyal to Saul's house until then;
131Ch 12:30 men of Ephraim, brave warriors, famous in their own clans--20,800;
131Ch 12:31 men of half the tribe of Manasseh, designated by name to come and make David king--18,000;
131Ch 12:32 men of Issachar, who understood the times and knew what Israel should do--200 chiefs, with all their relatives under their command;
131Ch 12:33 men of Zebulun, experienced soldiers prepared for battle with every type of weapon, to help David with undivided loyalty--50,000;
131Ch 12:34 men of Naphtali--1,000 officers, together with 37,000 men carrying shields and spears;
131Ch 12:35 men of Dan, ready for battle--28,600;
131Ch 12:36 men of Asher, experienced soldiers prepared for battle--40,000;
131Ch 12:37 and from east of the Jordan, men of Reuben, Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh, armed with every type of weapon--120,000.
131Ch 12:38 All these were fighting men who volunteered to serve in the ranks. They came to Hebron fully determined to make David king over all Israel. All the rest of the Israelites were also of one mind to make David king.
131Ch 12:39 The men spent three days there with David, eating and drinking, for their families had supplied provisions for them.
131Ch 12:40 Also, their neighbors from as far away as Issachar, Zebulun and Naphtali came bringing food on donkeys, camels, mules and oxen. There were plentiful supplies of flour, fig cakes, raisin cakes, wine, oil, cattle and sheep, for there was joy in Israel.
131Ch 13:1 David conferred with each of his officers, the commanders of thousands and commanders of hundreds.
131Ch 13:2 He then said to the whole assembly of Israel, "If it seems good to you and if it is the will of the LORD our God, let us send word far and wide to the rest of our brothers throughout the territories of Israel, and also to the priests and Levites who are with them in their towns and pasturelands, to come and join us.
131Ch 13:3 Let us bring the ark of our God back to us, for we did not inquire of it during the reign of Saul."
131Ch 13:4 The whole assembly agreed to do this, because it seemed right to all the people.
131Ch 13:5 So David assembled all the Israelites, from the Shihor River in Egypt to Lebo Hamath, to bring the ark of God from Kiriath Jearim.
131Ch 13:6 David and all the Israelites with him went to Baalah of Judah (Kiriath Jearim) to bring up from there the ark of God the LORD, who is enthroned between the cherubim--the ark that is called by the Name.
131Ch 13:7 They moved the ark of God from Abinadab's house on a new cart, with Uzzah and Ahio guiding it.
131Ch 13:8 David and all the Israelites were celebrating with all their might before God, with songs and with harps, lyres, tambourines, cymbals and trumpets.
131Ch 13:9 When they came to the threshing floor of Kidon, Uzzah reached out his hand to steady the ark, because the oxen stumbled.
131Ch 13:10 The LORD'S anger burned against Uzzah, and he struck him down because he had put his hand on the ark. So he died there before God.
131Ch 13:11 Then David was angry because the LORD'S wrath had broken out against Uzzah, and to this day that place is called Perez Uzzah.
131Ch 13:12 David was afraid of God that day and asked, "How can I ever bring the ark of God to me?"
131Ch 13:13 He did not take the ark to be with him in the City of David. Instead, he took it aside to the house of Obed-Edom the Gittite.
131Ch 13:14 The ark of God remained with the family of Obed-Edom in his house for three months, and the LORD blessed his household and everything he had.
131Ch 14:1 Now Hiram king of Tyre sent messengers to David, along with cedar logs, stonemasons and carpenters to build a palace for him.
131Ch 14:2 And David knew that the LORD had established him as king over Israel and that his kingdom had been highly exalted for the sake of his people Israel.
131Ch 14:3 In Jerusalem David took more wives and became the father of more sons and daughters.
131Ch 14:4 These are the names of the children born to him there£º Shammua, Shobab, Nathan, Solomon,
131Ch 14:5 Ibhar, Elishua, Elpelet,
131Ch 14:6 Nogah, Nepheg, Japhia,
131Ch 14:7 Elishama, Beeliada and Eliphelet.
131Ch 14:8 When the Philistines heard that David had been anointed king over all Israel, they went up in full force to search for him, but David heard about it and went out to meet them.
131Ch 14:9 Now the Philistines had come and raided the Valley of Rephaim;
131Ch 14:10 so David inquired of God£º "Shall I go and attack the Philistines? Will you hand them over to me?" The LORD answered him, "Go, I will hand them over to you."
131Ch 14:11 So David and his men went up to Baal Perazim, and there he defeated them. He said, "As waters break out, God has broken out against my enemies by my hand." So that place was called Baal Perazim.
131Ch 14:12 The Philistines had abandoned their gods there, and David gave orders to burn them in the fire.
131Ch 14:13 Once more the Philistines raided the valley;
131Ch 14:14 so David inquired of God again, and God answered him, "Do not go straight up, but circle around them and attack them in front of the balsam trees.
131Ch 14:15 As soon as you hear the sound of marching in the tops of the balsam trees, move out to battle, because that will mean God has gone out in front of you to strike the Philistine army."
131Ch 14:16 So David did as God commanded him, and they struck down the Philistine army, all the way from Gibeon to Gezer.
131Ch 14:17 So David's fame spread throughout every land, and the LORD made all the nations fear him.
131Ch 15:1 After David had constructed buildings for himself in the City of David, he prepared a place for the ark of God and pitched a tent for it.
131Ch 15:2 Then David said, "No one but the Levites may carry the ark of God, because the LORD chose them to carry the ark of the LORD and to minister before him forever."
131Ch 15:3 David assembled all Israel in Jerusalem to bring up the ark of the LORD to the place he had prepared for it.
131Ch 15:4 He called together the descendants of Aaron and the Levites£º
131Ch 15:5 From the descendants of Kohath, Uriel the leader and 120 relatives;
131Ch 15:6 from the descendants of Merari, Asaiah the leader and 220 relatives;
131Ch 15:7 from the descendants of Gershon, Joel the leader and 130 relatives;
131Ch 15:8 from the descendants of Elizaphan, Shemaiah the leader and 200 relatives;
131Ch 15:9 from the descendants of Hebron, Eliel the leader and 80 relatives;
131Ch 15:10 from the descendants of Uzziel, Amminadab the leader and 112 relatives.
131Ch 15:11 Then David summoned Zadok and Abiathar the priests, and Uriel, Asaiah, Joel, Shemaiah, Eliel and Amminadab the Levites.
131Ch 15:12 He said to them, "You are the heads of the Levitical families; you and your fellow Levites are to consecrate yourselves and bring up the ark of the LORD, the God of Israel, to the place I have prepared for it.
131Ch 15:13 It was because you, the Levites, did not bring it up the first time that the LORD our God broke out in anger against us. We did not inquire of him about how to do it in the prescribed way."
131Ch 15:14 So the priests and Levites consecrated themselves in order to bring up the ark of the LORD, the God of Israel.
131Ch 15:15 And the Levites carried the ark of God with the poles on their shoulders, as Moses had commanded in accordance with the word of the LORD.
131Ch 15:16 David told the leaders of the Levites to appoint their brothers as singers to sing joyful songs, accompanied by musical instruments£º lyres, harps and cymbals.
131Ch 15:17 So the Levites appointed Heman son of Joel; from his brothers, Asaph son of Berekiah; and from their brothers the Merarites, Ethan son of Kushaiah;
131Ch 15:18 and with them their brothers next in rank£º Zechariah, Jaaziel, Shemiramoth, Jehiel, Unni, Eliab, Benaiah, Maaseiah, Mattithiah, Eliphelehu, Mikneiah, Obed-Edom and Jeiel, the gatekeepers.
131Ch 15:19 The musicians Heman, Asaph and Ethan were to sound the bronze cymbals;
131Ch 15:20 Zechariah, Aziel, Shemiramoth, Jehiel, Unni, Eliab, Maaseiah and Benaiah were to play the lyres according to alamoth,
131Ch 15:21 and Mattithiah, Eliphelehu, Mikneiah, Obed-Edom, Jeiel and Azaziah were to play the harps, directing according to sheminith.
131Ch 15:22 Kenaniah the head Levite was in charge of the singing; that was his responsibility because he was skillful at it.
131Ch 15:23 Berekiah and Elkanah were to be doorkeepers for the ark.
131Ch 15:24 Shebaniah, Joshaphat, Nethanel, Amasai, Zechariah, Benaiah and Eliezer the priests were to blow trumpets before the ark of God. Obed-Edom and Jehiah were also to be doorkeepers for the ark.
131Ch 15:25 So David and the elders of Israel and the commanders of units of a thousand went to bring up the ark of the covenant of the LORD from the house of Obed-Edom, with rejoicing.
131Ch 15:26 Because God had helped the Levites who were carrying the ark of the covenant of the LORD, seven bulls and seven rams were sacrificed.
131Ch 15:27 Now David was clothed in a robe of fine linen, as were all the Levites who were carrying the ark, and as were the singers, and Kenaniah, who was in charge of the singing of the choirs. David also wore a linen ephod.
131Ch 15:28 So all Israel brought up the ark of the covenant of the LORD with shouts, with the sounding of rams' horns and trumpets, and of cymbals, and the playing of lyres and harps.
131Ch 15:29 As the ark of the covenant of the LORD was entering the City of David, Michal daughter of Saul watched from a window. And when she saw King David dancing and celebrating, she despised him in her heart.
131Ch 16:1 They brought the ark of God and set it inside the tent that David had pitched for it, and they presented burnt offerings and fellowship offerings before God.
131Ch 16:2 After David had finished sacrificing the burnt offerings and fellowship offerings, he blessed the people in the name of the LORD.
131Ch 16:3 Then he gave a loaf of bread, a cake of dates and a cake of raisins to each Israelite man and woman.
131Ch 16:4 He appointed some of the Levites to minister before the ark of the LORD, to make petition, to give thanks, and to praise the LORD, the God of Israel£º
131Ch 16:5 Asaph was the chief, Zechariah second, then Jeiel, Shemiramoth, Jehiel, Mattithiah, Eliab, Benaiah, Obed-Edom and Jeiel. They were to play the lyres and harps, Asaph was to sound the cymbals,
131Ch 16:6 and Benaiah and Jahaziel the priests were to blow the trumpets regularly before the ark of the covenant of God.
131Ch 16:7 That day David first committed to Asaph and his associates this psalm of thanks to the LORD£º
131Ch 16:8 Give thanks to the LORD, call on his name; make known among the nations what he has done.
131Ch 16:9 Sing to him, sing praise to him; tell of all his wonderful acts.
131Ch 16:10 Glory in his holy name; let the hearts of those who seek the LORD rejoice.
131Ch 16:11 Look to the LORD and his strength; seek his face always.
131Ch 16:12 Remember the wonders he has done, his miracles, and the judgments he pronounced,
131Ch 16:13 O descendants of Israel his servant, O sons of Jacob, his chosen ones.
131Ch 16:14 He is the LORD our God; his judgments are in all the earth.
131Ch 16:15 He remembers his covenant forever, the word he commanded, for a thousand generations,
131Ch 16:16 the covenant he made with Abraham, the oath he swore to Isaac.
131Ch 16:17 He confirmed it to Jacob as a decree, to Israel as an everlasting covenant£º
131Ch 16:18 "To you I will give the land of Canaan as the portion you will inherit."
131Ch 16:19 When they were but few in number, few indeed, and strangers in it,
131Ch 16:20 they wandered from nation to nation, from one kingdom to another.
131Ch 16:21 He allowed no man to oppress them; for their sake he rebuked kings£º
131Ch 16:22 "Do not touch my anointed ones; do my prophets no harm."
131Ch 16:23 Sing to the LORD, all the earth; proclaim his salvation day after day.
131Ch 16:24 Declare his glory among the nations, his marvelous deeds among all peoples.
131Ch 16:25 For great is the LORD and most worthy of praise; he is to be feared above all gods.
131Ch 16:26 For all the gods of the nations are idols, but the LORD made the heavens.
131Ch 16:27 Splendor and majesty are before him; strength and joy in his dwelling place.
131Ch 16:28 Ascribe to the LORD, O families of nations, ascribe to the LORD glory and strength,
131Ch 16:29 ascribe to the LORD the glory due his name. Bring an offering and come before him; worship the LORD in the splendor of his holiness.
131Ch 16:30 Tremble before him, all the earth! The world is firmly established; it cannot be moved.
131Ch 16:31 Let the heavens rejoice, let the earth be glad; let them say among the nations, "The LORD reigns!"
131Ch 16:32 Let the sea resound, and all that is in it; let the fields be jubilant, and everything in them!
131Ch 16:33 Then the trees of the forest will sing, they will sing for joy before the LORD, for he comes to judge the earth.
131Ch 16:34 Give thanks to the LORD, for he is good; his love endures forever.
131Ch 16:35 Cry out, "Save us, O God our Savior; gather us and deliver us from the nations, that we may give thanks to your holy name, that we may glory in your praise."
131Ch 16:36 Praise be to the LORD, the God of Israel, from everlasting to everlasting. Then all the people said "Amen" and "Praise the LORD."
131Ch 16:37 David left Asaph and his associates before the ark of the covenant of the LORD to minister there regularly, according to each day's requirements.
131Ch 16:38 He also left Obed-Edom and his sixty-eight associates to minister with them. Obed-Edom son of Jeduthun, and also Hosah, were gatekeepers.
131Ch 16:39 David left Zadok the priest and his fellow priests before the tabernacle of the LORD at the high place in Gibeon
131Ch 16:40 to present burnt offerings to the LORD on the altar of burnt offering regularly, morning and evening, in accordance with everything written in the Law of the LORD, which he had given Israel.
131Ch 16:41 With them were Heman and Jeduthun and the rest of those chosen and designated by name to give thanks to the LORD, "for his love endures forever."
131Ch 16:42 Heman and Jeduthun were responsible for the sounding of the trumpets and cymbals and for the playing of the other instruments for sacred song. The sons of Jeduthun were stationed at the gate.
131Ch 16:43 Then all the people left, each for his own home, and David returned home to bless his family.
131Ch 17:1 After David was settled in his palace, he said to Nathan the prophet, "Here I am, living in a palace of cedar, while the ark of the covenant of the LORD is under a tent."
131Ch 17:2 Nathan replied to David, "Whatever you have in mind, do it, for God is with you."
131Ch 17:3 That night the word of God came to Nathan, saying£º
131Ch 17:4 "Go and tell my servant David, 'This is what the LORD says£º You are not the one to build me a house to dwell in.
131Ch 17:5 I have not dwelt in a house from the day I brought Israel up out of Egypt to this day. I have moved from one tent site to another, from one dwelling place to another.
131Ch 17:6 Wherever I have moved with all the Israelites, did I ever say to any of their leaders whom I commanded to shepherd my people, "Why have you not built me a house of cedar?" '
131Ch 17:7 "Now then, tell my servant David, 'This is what the LORD Almighty says£º I took you from the pasture and from following the flock, to be ruler over my people Israel.
131Ch 17:8 I have been with you wherever you have gone, and I have cut off all your enemies from before you. Now I will make your name like the names of the greatest men of the earth.
131Ch 17:9 And I will provide a place for my people Israel and will plant them so that they can have a home of their own and no longer be disturbed. Wicked people will not oppress them anymore, as they did at the beginning
131Ch 17:10 and have done ever since the time I appointed leaders over my people Israel. I will also subdue all your enemies. "'I declare to you that the LORD will build a house for you£º
131Ch 17:11 When your days are over and you go to be with your fathers, I will raise up your offspring to succeed you, one of your own sons, and I will establish his kingdom.
131Ch 17:12 He is the one who will build a house for me, and I will establish his throne forever.
131Ch 17:13 I will be his father, and he will be my son. I will never take my love away from him, as I took it away from your predecessor.
131Ch 17:14 I will set him over my house and my kingdom forever; his throne will be established forever.'"
131Ch 17:15 Nathan reported to David all the words of this entire revelation.
131Ch 17:16 Then King David went in and sat before the LORD, and he said£º "Who am I, O LORD God, and what is my family, that you have brought me this far?
131Ch 17:17 And as if this were not enough in your sight, O God, you have spoken about the future of the house of your servant. You have looked on me as though I were the most exalted of men, O LORD God.
131Ch 17:18 "What more can David say to you for honoring your servant? For you know your servant,
131Ch 17:19 O LORD. For the sake of your servant and according to your will, you have done this great thing and made known all these great promises.
131Ch 17:20 "There is no one like you, O LORD, and there is no God but you, as we have heard with our own ears.
131Ch 17:21 And who is like your people Israel--the one nation on earth whose God went out to redeem a people for himself, and to make a name for yourself, and to perform great and awesome wonders by driving out nations from before your people, whom you redeemed from Egypt?
131Ch 17:22 You made your people Israel your very own forever, and you, O LORD, have become their God.
131Ch 17:23 "And now, LORD, let the promise you have made concerning your servant and his house be established forever. Do as you promised,
131Ch 17:24 so that it will be established and that your name will be great forever. Then men will say, 'The LORD Almighty, the God over Israel, is Israel's God!' And the house of your servant David will be established before you.
131Ch 17:25 "You, my God, have revealed to your servant that you will build a house for him. So your servant has found courage to pray to you.
131Ch 17:26 O LORD, you are God! You have promised these good things to your servant.
131Ch 17:27 Now you have been pleased to bless the house of your servant, that it may continue forever in your sight; for you, O LORD, have blessed it, and it will be blessed forever."
131Ch 18:1 In the course of time, David defeated the Philistines and subdued them, and he took Gath and its surrounding villages from the control of the Philistines.
131Ch 18:2 David also defeated the Moabites, and they became subject to him and brought tribute.
131Ch 18:3 Moreover, David fought Hadadezer king of Zobah, as far as Hamath, when he went to establish his control along the Euphrates River.
131Ch 18:4 David captured a thousand of his chariots, seven thousand charioteers and twenty thousand foot soldiers. He hamstrung all but a hundred of the chariot horses.
131Ch 18:5 When the Arameans of Damascus came to help Hadadezer king of Zobah, David struck down twenty-two thousand of them.
131Ch 18:6 He put garrisons in the Aramean kingdom of Damascus, and the Arameans became subject to him and brought tribute. The LORD gave David victory everywhere he went.
131Ch 18:7 David took the gold shields carried by the officers of Hadadezer and brought them to Jerusalem.
131Ch 18:8 From Tebah and Cun, towns that belonged to Hadadezer, David took a great quantity of bronze, which Solomon used to make the bronze Sea, the pillars and various bronze articles.
131Ch 18:9 When Tou king of Hamath heard that David had defeated the entire army of Hadadezer king of Zobah,
131Ch 18:10 he sent his son Hadoram to King David to greet him and congratulate him on his victory in battle over Hadadezer, who had been at war with Tou. Hadoram brought all kinds of articles of gold and silver and bronze.
131Ch 18:11 King David dedicated these articles to the LORD, as he had done with the silver and gold he had taken from all these nations£º Edom and Moab, the Ammonites and the Philistines, and Amalek.
131Ch 18:12 Abishai son of Zeruiah struck down eighteen thousand Edomites in the Valley of Salt.
131Ch 18:13 He put garrisons in Edom, and all the Edomites became subject to David. The LORD gave David victory everywhere he went.
131Ch 18:14 David reigned over all Israel, doing what was just and right for all his people.
131Ch 18:15 Joab son of Zeruiah was over the army; Jehoshaphat son of Ahilud was recorder;
131Ch 18:16 Zadok son of Ahitub and Ahimelech son of Abiathar were priests; Shavsha was secretary;
131Ch 18:17 Benaiah son of Jehoiada was over the Kerethites and Pelethites; and David's sons were chief officials at the king's side.
131Ch 19:1 In the course of time, Nahash king of the Ammonites died, and his son succeeded him as king.
131Ch 19:2 David thought, "I will show kindness to Hanun son of Nahash, because his father showed kindness to me." So David sent a delegation to express his sympathy to Hanun concerning his father. When David's men came to Hanun in the land of the Ammonites to express sympathy to him,
131Ch 19:3 the Ammonite nobles said to Hanun, "Do you think David is honoring your father by sending men to you to express sympathy? Haven't his men come to you to explore and spy out the country and overthrow it?"
131Ch 19:4 So Hanun seized David's men, shaved them, cut off their garments in the middle at the buttocks, and sent them away.
131Ch 19:5 When someone came and told David about the men, he sent messengers to meet them, for they were greatly humiliated. The king said, "Stay at Jericho till your beards have grown, and then come back."
131Ch 19:6 When the Ammonites realized that they had become a stench in David's nostrils, Hanun and the Ammonites sent a thousand talents of silver to hire chariots and charioteers from Aram Naharaim, Aram Maacah and Zobah.
131Ch 19:7 They hired thirty-two thousand chariots and charioteers, as well as the king of Maacah with his troops, who came and camped near Medeba, while the Ammonites were mustered from their towns and moved out for battle.
131Ch 19:8 On hearing this, David sent Joab out with the entire army of fighting men.
131Ch 19:9 The Ammonites came out and drew up in battle formation at the entrance to their city, while the kings who had come were by themselves in the open country.
131Ch 19:10 Joab saw that there were battle lines in front of him and behind him; so he selected some of the best troops in Israel and deployed them against the Arameans.
131Ch 19:11 He put the rest of the men under the command of Abishai his brother, and they were deployed against the Ammonites.
131Ch 19:12 Joab said, "If the Arameans are too strong for me, then you are to rescue me; but if the Ammonites are too strong for you, then I will rescue you.
131Ch 19:13 Be strong and let us fight bravely for our people and the cities of our God. The LORD will do what is good in his sight."
131Ch 19:14 Then Joab and the troops with him advanced to fight the Arameans, and they fled before him.
131Ch 19:15 When the Ammonites saw that the Arameans were fleeing, they too fled before his brother Abishai and went inside the city. So Joab went back to Jerusalem.
131Ch 19:16 After the Arameans saw that they had been routed by Israel, they sent messengers and had Arameans brought from beyond the River, with Shophach the commander of Hadadezer's army leading them.
131Ch 19:17 When David was told of this, he gathered all Israel and crossed the Jordan; he advanced against them and formed his battle lines opposite them. David formed his lines to meet the Arameans in battle, and they fought against him.
131Ch 19:18 But they fled before Israel, and David killed seven thousand of their charioteers and forty thousand of their foot soldiers. He also killed Shophach the commander of their army.
131Ch 19:19 When the vassals of Hadadezer saw that they had been defeated by Israel, they made peace with David and became subject to him. So the Arameans were not willing to help the Ammonites anymore.
131Ch 20:1 In the spring, at the time when kings go off to war, Joab led out the armed forces. He laid waste the land of the Ammonites and went to Rabbah and besieged it, but David remained in Jerusalem. Joab attacked Rabbah and left it in ruins.
131Ch 20:2 David took the crown from the head of their king--its weight was found to be a talent of gold, and it was set with precious stones--and it was placed on David's head. He took a great quantity of plunder from the city
131Ch 20:3 and brought out the people who were there, consigning them to labor with saws and with iron picks and axes. David did this to all the Ammonite towns. Then David and his entire army returned to Jerusalem.
131Ch 20:4 In the course of time, war broke out with the Philistines, at Gezer. At that time Sibbecai the Hushathite killed Sippai, one of the descendants of the Rephaites, and the Philistines were subjugated.
131Ch 20:5 In another battle with the Philistines, Elhanan son of Jair killed Lahmi the brother of Goliath the Gittite, who had a spear with a shaft like a weaver's rod.
131Ch 20:6 In still another battle, which took place at Gath, there was a huge man with six fingers on each hand and six toes on each foot--twenty-four in all. He also was descended from Rapha.
131Ch 20:7 When he taunted Israel, Jonathan son of Shimea, David's brother, killed him.
131Ch 20:8 These were descendants of Rapha in Gath, and they fell at the hands of David and his men.
131Ch 21:1 Satan rose up against Israel and incited David to take a census of Israel.
131Ch 21:2 So David said to Joab and the commanders of the troops, "Go and count the Israelites from Beersheba to Dan. Then report back to me so that I may know how many there are."
131Ch 21:3 But Joab replied, "May the LORD multiply his troops a hundred times over. My lord the king, are they not all my lord's subjects? Why does my lord want to do this? Why should he bring guilt on Israel?"
131Ch 21:4 The king's word, however, overruled Joab; so Joab left and went throughout Israel and then came back to Jerusalem.
131Ch 21:5 Joab reported the number of the fighting men to David£º In all Israel there were one million one hundred thousand men who could handle a sword, including four hundred and seventy thousand in Judah.
131Ch 21:6 But Joab did not include Levi and Benjamin in the numbering, because the king's command was repulsive to him.
131Ch 21:7 This command was also evil in the sight of God; so he punished Israel.
131Ch 21:8 Then David said to God, "I have sinned greatly by doing this. Now, I beg you, take away the guilt of your servant. I have done a very foolish thing."
131Ch 21:9 The LORD said to Gad, David's seer,
131Ch 21:10 "Go and tell David, 'This is what the LORD says£º I am giving you three options. Choose one of them for me to carry out against you.'"
131Ch 21:11 So Gad went to David and said to him, "This is what the LORD says£º 'Take your choice£º
131Ch 21:12 three years of famine, three months of being swept away before your enemies, with their swords overtaking you, or three days of the sword of the LORD--days of plague in the land, with the angel of the LORD ravaging every part of Israel.' Now then, decide how I should answer the one who sent me."
131Ch 21:13 David said to Gad, "I am in deep distress. Let me fall into the hands of the LORD, for his mercy is very great; but do not let me fall into the hands of men."
131Ch 21:14 So the LORD sent a plague on Israel, and seventy thousand men of Israel fell dead.
131Ch 21:15 And God sent an angel to destroy Jerusalem. But as the angel was doing so, the LORD saw it and was grieved because of the calamity and said to the angel who was destroying the people, "Enough! Withdraw your hand." The angel of the LORD was then standing at the threshing floor of Araunah the Jebusite.
131Ch 21:16 David looked up and saw the angel of the LORD standing between heaven and earth, with a drawn sword in his hand extended over Jerusalem. Then David and the elders, clothed in sackcloth, fell facedown.
131Ch 21:17 David said to God, "Was it not I who ordered the fighting men to be counted? I am the one who has sinned and done wrong. These are but sheep. What have they done? O LORD my God, let your hand fall upon me and my family, but do not let this plague remain on your people."
131Ch 21:18 Then the angel of the LORD ordered Gad to tell David to go up and build an altar to the LORD on the threshing floor of Araunah the Jebusite.
131Ch 21:19 So David went up in obedience to the word that Gad had spoken in the name of the LORD.
131Ch 21:20 While Araunah was threshing wheat, he turned and saw the angel; his four sons who were with him hid themselves.
131Ch 21:21 Then David approached, and when Araunah looked and saw him, he left the threshing floor and bowed down before David with his face to the ground.
131Ch 21:22 David said to him, "Let me have the site of your threshing floor so I can build an altar to the LORD, that the plague on the people may be stopped. Sell it to me at the full price."
131Ch 21:23 Araunah said to David, "Take it! Let my lord the king do whatever pleases him. Look, I will give the oxen for the burnt offerings, the threshing sledges for the wood, and the wheat for the grain offering. I will give all this."
131Ch 21:24 But King David replied to Araunah, "No, I insist on paying the full price. I will not take for the LORD what is yours, or sacrifice a burnt offering that costs me nothing."
131Ch 21:25 So David paid Araunah six hundred shekels of gold for the site.
131Ch 21:26 David built an altar to the LORD there and sacrificed burnt offerings and fellowship offerings. He called on the LORD, and the LORD answered him with fire from heaven on the altar of burnt offering.
131Ch 21:27 Then the LORD spoke to the angel, and he put his sword back into its sheath.
131Ch 21:28 At that time, when David saw that the LORD had answered him on the threshing floor of Araunah the Jebusite, he offered sacrifices there.
131Ch 21:29 The tabernacle of the LORD, which Moses had made in the desert, and the altar of burnt offering were at that time on the high place at Gibeon.
131Ch 21:30 But David could not go before it to inquire of God, because he was afraid of the sword of the angel of the LORD.
131Ch 22:1 Then David said, "The house of the LORD God is to be here, and also the altar of burnt offering for Israel."
131Ch 22:2 So David gave orders to assemble the aliens living in Israel, and from among them he appointed stonecutters to prepare dressed stone for building the house of God.
131Ch 22:3 He provided a large amount of iron to make nails for the doors of the gateways and for the fittings, and more bronze than could be weighed.
131Ch 22:4 He also provided more cedar logs than could be counted, for the Sidonians and Tyrians had brought large numbers of them to David.
131Ch 22:5 David said, "My son Solomon is young and inexperienced, and the house to be built for the LORD should be of great magnificence and fame and splendor in the sight of all the nations. Therefore I will make preparations for it." So David made extensive preparations before his death.
131Ch 22:6 Then he called for his son Solomon and charged him to build a house for the LORD, the God of Israel.
131Ch 22:7 David said to Solomon£º "My son, I had it in my heart to build a house for the Name of the LORD my God.
131Ch 22:8 But this word of the LORD came to me£º 'You have shed much blood and have fought many wars. You are not to build a house for my Name, because you have shed much blood on the earth in my sight.
131Ch 22:9 But you will have a son who will be a man of peace and rest, and I will give him rest from all his enemies on every side. His name will be Solomon, and I will grant Israel peace and quiet during his reign.
131Ch 22:10 He is the one who will build a house for my Name. He will be my son, and I will be his father. And I will establish the throne of his kingdom over Israel forever.'
131Ch 22:11 "Now, my son, the LORD be with you, and may you have success and build the house of the LORD your God, as he said you would.
131Ch 22:12 May the LORD give you discretion and understanding when he puts you in command over Israel, so that you may keep the law of the LORD your God.
131Ch 22:13 Then you will have success if you are careful to observe the decrees and laws that the LORD gave Moses for Israel. Be strong and courageous. Do not be afraid or discouraged.
131Ch 22:14 "I have taken great pains to provide for the temple of the LORD a hundred thousand talents of gold, a million talents of silver, quantities of bronze and iron too great to be weighed, and wood and stone. And you may add to them.
131Ch 22:15 You have many workmen£º stonecutters, masons and carpenters, as well as men skilled in every kind of work
131Ch 22:16 in gold and silver, bronze and iron--craftsmen beyond number. Now begin the work, and the LORD be with you."
131Ch 22:17 Then David ordered all the leaders of Israel to help his son Solomon.
131Ch 22:18 He said to them, "Is not the LORD your God with you? And has he not granted you rest on every side? For he has handed the inhabitants of the land over to me, and the land is subject to the LORD and to his people.
131Ch 22:19 Now devote your heart and soul to seeking the LORD your God. Begin to build the sanctuary of the LORD God, so that you may bring the ark of the covenant of the LORD and the sacred articles belonging to God into the temple that will be built for the Name of the LORD."
131Ch 23:1 When David was old and full of years, he made his son Solomon king over Israel.
131Ch 23:2 He also gathered together all the leaders of Israel, as well as the priests and Levites.
131Ch 23:3 The Levites thirty years old or more were counted, and the total number of men was thirty-eight thousand.
131Ch 23:4 David said, "Of these, twenty-four thousand are to supervise the work of the temple of the LORD and six thousand are to be officials and judges.
131Ch 23:5 Four thousand are to be gatekeepers and four thousand are to praise the LORD with the musical instruments I have provided for that purpose."
131Ch 23:6 David divided the Levites into groups corresponding to the sons of Levi£º Gershon, Kohath and Merari.
131Ch 23:7 Belonging to the Gershonites£º Ladan and Shimei.
131Ch 23:8 The sons of Ladan£º Jehiel the first, Zetham and Joel--three in all.
131Ch 23:9 The sons of Shimei£º Shelomoth, Haziel and Haran--three in all. These were the heads of the families of Ladan.
131Ch 23:10 And the sons of Shimei£º Jahath, Ziza, Jeush and Beriah. These were the sons of Shimei--four in all.
131Ch 23:11 Jahath was the first and Ziza the second, but Jeush and Beriah did not have many sons; so they were counted as one family with one assignment.
131Ch 23:12 The sons of Kohath£º Amram, Izhar, Hebron and Uzziel--four in all.
131Ch 23:13 The sons of Amram£º Aaron and Moses. Aaron was set apart, he and his descendants forever, to consecrate the most holy things, to offer sacrifices before the LORD, to minister before him and to pronounce blessings in his name forever.
131Ch 23:14 The sons of Moses the man of God were counted as part of the tribe of Levi.
131Ch 23:15 The sons of Moses£º Gershom and Eliezer.
131Ch 23:16 The descendants of Gershom£º Shubael was the first.
131Ch 23:17 The descendants of Eliezer£º Rehabiah was the first. Eliezer had no other sons, but the sons of Rehabiah were very numerous.
131Ch 23:18 The sons of Izhar£º Shelomith was the first.
131Ch 23:19 The sons of Hebron£º Jeriah the first, Amariah the second, Jahaziel the third and Jekameam the fourth.
131Ch 23:20 The sons of Uzziel£º Micah the first and Isshiah the second.
131Ch 23:21 The sons of Merari£º Mahli and Mushi. The sons of Mahli£º Eleazar and Kish.
131Ch 23:22 Eleazar died without having sons£º he had only daughters. Their cousins, the sons of Kish, married them.
131Ch 23:23 The sons of Mushi£º Mahli, Eder and Jerimoth--three in all.
131Ch 23:24 These were the descendants of Levi by their families--the heads of families as they were registered under their names and counted individually, that is, the workers twenty years old or more who served in the temple of the LORD.
131Ch 23:25 For David had said, "Since the LORD, the God of Israel, has granted rest to his people and has come to dwell in Jerusalem forever,
131Ch 23:26 the Levites no longer need to carry the tabernacle or any of the articles used in its service."
131Ch 23:27 According to the last instructions of David, the Levites were counted from those twenty years old or more.
131Ch 23:28 The duty of the Levites was to help Aaron's descendants in the service of the temple of the LORD£º to be in charge of the courtyards, the side rooms, the purification of all sacred things and the performance of other duties at the house of God.
131Ch 23:29 They were in charge of the bread set out on the table, the flour for the grain offerings, the unleavened wafers, the baking and the mixing, and all measurements of quantity and size.
131Ch 23:30 They were also to stand every morning to thank and praise the LORD. They were to do the same in the evening
131Ch 23:31 and whenever burnt offerings were presented to the LORD on Sabbaths and at New Moon festivals and at appointed feasts. They were to serve before the LORD regularly in the proper number and in the way prescribed for them.
131Ch 23:32 And so the Levites carried out their responsibilities for the Tent of Meeting, for the Holy Place and, under their brothers the descendants of Aaron, for the service of the temple of the LORD.
131Ch 24:1 These were the divisions of the sons of Aaron£º The sons of Aaron were Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar and Ithamar.
131Ch 24:2 But Nadab and Abihu died before their father did, and they had no sons; so Eleazar and Ithamar served as the priests.
131Ch 24:3 With the help of Zadok a descendant of Eleazar and Ahimelech a descendant of Ithamar, David separated them into divisions for their appointed order of ministering.
131Ch 24:4 A larger number of leaders were found among Eleazar's descendants than among Ithamar's, and they were divided accordingly£º sixteen heads of families from Eleazar's descendants and eight heads of families from Ithamar's descendants.
131Ch 24:5 They divided them impartially by drawing lots, for there were officials of the sanctuary and officials of God among the descendants of both Eleazar and Ithamar.
131Ch 24:6 The scribe Shemaiah son of Nethanel, a Levite, recorded their names in the presence of the king and of the officials£º Zadok the priest, Ahimelech son of Abiathar and the heads of families of the priests and of the Levites--one family being taken from Eleazar and then one from Ithamar.
131Ch 24:7 The first lot fell to Jehoiarib, the second to Jedaiah,
131Ch 24:8 the third to Harim, the fourth to Seorim,
131Ch 24:9 the fifth to Malkijah, the sixth to Mijamin,
131Ch 24:10 the seventh to Hakkoz, the eighth to Abijah,
131Ch 24:11 the ninth to Jeshua, the tenth to Shecaniah,
131Ch 24:12 the eleventh to Eliashib, the twelfth to Jakim,
131Ch 24:13 the thirteenth to Huppah, the fourteenth to Jeshebeab,
131Ch 24:14 the fifteenth to Bilgah, the sixteenth to Immer,
131Ch 24:15 the seventeenth to Hezir, the eighteenth to Happizzez,
131Ch 24:16 the nineteenth to Pethahiah, the twentieth to Jehezkel,
131Ch 24:17 the twenty-first to Jakin, the twenty-second to Gamul,
131Ch 24:18 the twenty-third to Delaiah and the twenty-fourth to Maaziah.
131Ch 24:19 This was their appointed order of ministering when they entered the temple of the LORD, according to the regulations prescribed for them by their forefather Aaron, as the LORD, the God of Israel, had commanded him.
131Ch 24:20 As for the rest of the descendants of Levi£º from the sons of Amram£º Shubael; from the sons of Shubael£º Jehdeiah.
131Ch 24:21 As for Rehabiah, from his sons£º Isshiah was the first.
131Ch 24:22 From the Izharites£º Shelomoth; from the sons of Shelomoth£º Jahath.
131Ch 24:23 The sons of Hebron£º Jeriah the first, Amariah the second, Jahaziel the third and Jekameam the fourth.
131Ch 24:24 The son of Uzziel£º Micah; from the sons of Micah£º Shamir.
131Ch 24:25 The brother of Micah£º Isshiah; from the sons of Isshiah£º Zechariah.
131Ch 24:26 The sons of Merari£º Mahli and Mushi. The son of Jaaziah£º Beno.
131Ch 24:27 The sons of Merari£º from Jaaziah£º Beno, Shoham, Zaccur and Ibri.
131Ch 24:28 From Mahli£º Eleazar, who had no sons.
131Ch 24:29 From Kish£º the son of Kish£º Jerahmeel.
131Ch 24:30 And the sons of Mushi£º Mahli, Eder and Jerimoth. These were the Levites, according to their families.
131Ch 24:31 They also cast lots, just as their brothers the descendants of Aaron did, in the presence of King David and of Zadok, Ahimelech, and the heads of families of the priests and of the Levites. The families of the oldest brother were treated the same as those of the youngest.
